source: # SDR Scheduled: Exploratory Data Analysis

This notebook is to showcase stats for SDR scheduled demos by Marketing Channel, Day of the Week, Landing Page, and Sales Rep from May 1, 2020 - September 14, 2020.

May 2020 - Today Stats:üí£Ô∏èüí£Ô∏èüí•üí•

  • 7334 Leads
  • 73% of Total Lead Volume
  • 1036 Scheduled Demos
  • 14 SDR Scheduled Rate%
  • 28% of Total Scheduled Demos are from SDR Team

#Import packages for analysis

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from pandas import Series, DataFrame
import matplotlib as mpl
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import plotly.graph_objects as go
#import dataset
sdr = pd.read_csv('SDR_Scheduled_Since_May.csv', header =0)

sdr.head()
# Overview
Table below shows that since May 2020, the average SDR scheduled cycle is 3 Days, and the longest is 31 Days. This data set includes 972 SDR scheduled
sdr.describe()
# Correlation Matrix

The chart below shows how aspects of SDR scheduled leads are correlated.

For SDR Scheduled Cycle, there is a slight correlation with Marketing Channel, The Day of the week, and Landing Page.

This means that there are different days and channels  schedule at higher/lower rates, but don't vary from one to another in a massive way. This is a good thing because, in the case of marketing channels, it tells us that there isn't one that's really bad, or really good, though some performane better than others.

ü§ìFeatures that make the difference for scheduled cycle:

1. Marketing Channel

2. Landing Page

3. Day Lead Came in

str_list = [] # empty list to contain columns with strings (words)
for colname, colvalue in sdr.iteritems():
    if type(colvalue[1]) == str:
         str_list.append(colname)
# Get to the numeric columns by inversion            
num_list = sdr.columns.difference(str_list) 
# Create Dataframe containing only numerical features
house_num = sdr[num_list]
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.title('SDR Correlated Features')
# Draw the heatmap using seaborn
#sns.heatmap(house_num.astype(float).corr(),linewidths=0.25,vmax=1.0, square=True, cmap="PuBuGn", linecolor='k', annot=True)
sns.heatmap(house_num.astype(float).corr(),linewidths=0.2,vmax=1.0, square=False, cmap="cubehelix", linecolor='k', annot=True)
# Exploratory Data Analysis
This section provides analysis on the SDR days to schedule by Marketing Channel, Landing Page, and Day
48% of SDR scheduled leads are same day
g = sns.catplot('Cycle_length', data=sdr, kind='count', aspect=2.5,palette='RdBu')
g.set_xlabels('SDR Days to Schedule Since May 2020', size=18)
Metrics from chart above
sdr.groupby('Cycle_length')['Cycle_length'].count()
#creating new data set for only same day schedules to use later
sdrsd = sdr[(sdr['Cycle_length']== 0)]
# Stats By Channel and Day
<b>Scheduled Demos by Channel and Day

Findings:

1. Wednesday is the top day for same day schedules for paid leads
2. Monday and Tuesday are solid days for 1 day BDR Scheduled
3. Friday is one of the top day week day for Social and Organic, but worst for CPC
4. Since May there have been no scheduled demos from Wendesday leads, but there have been some from Tuesday
sns.catplot('Cycle_length', data=sdrchannel, col='Day_', kind='count', hue='Channel_', order=[0,1,2,3,4], aspect=.5)
sdrchannel = sdr.loc[(sdr['Channel_'] == 'cpc') | (sdr['Channel_'] == 'social')| (sdr['Channel_'] == 'organic')]
